title: Common English Vocabulary Words that Start with E

json.text: Welcome to PnT English channel. A learning vocabulary with videos channel.
Welcome to the oxford 3000 essential words program. Now, let's start learning English!
Section 5: Words Starting with E. each. e . a . c . h . each. each means to
or from every one of two or more (considered individually). They received $10 each.
each other. each other. each other means each member of a group does something to the others
or has a particular connection with the others. We can wear each other's clothes.
eager. e . a . g . e . r . eager. eager means having or showing keen interest or intense
desire or impatient expectancy. Eager to travel abroad.
ear. e . a . r . ear. ears ears are the two parts of your body that you hear with. She
tucked her hair behind her ears. early. e . a . r . l . y . early. early means
at or near the beginning of a period of time or course of events or before the usual or
expected time. An early spring. earn. e . a . r . n . earn. earn means earn
on some commercial or business transaction; earn as salary or wages. She earns a lot in
her new job earth. e . a . r . t . h . earth. earth is
the loose soft material that makes up a large part of the land surface. They dug into the
earth outside the church. ease. e . a . s . e . ease. ease means freedom
from difficulty or hardship or effort. He rose through the ranks with apparent ease.
east. e . a . s . t . east. east means situated in or facing or moving toward the east. A
low line of hills running along the east coast. eastern. e . a . s . t . e . r . n . eastern.
eastern means lying toward or situated in the east. The eastern end of the island.
easy. e . a . s . y . easy. easy means posing no difficulty; requiring little effort. Took
the easy way out of his dilemma. easily. e . a . s . i . l . y . easily. easily
means with ease easy is sometimes used informally for easily. This china breaks very easily.
eat. e . a . t . eat. eat means take in solid food. She was eating a banana.
economic. e . c . o . n . o . m . i . c . economic. economic means of or relating to an economy,
the system of production and management of material wealth. Aspects of social, political,
and economic life. economics. e . c . o . n . o . m . i . c . s
. economics. economics means the branch of social science that deals with the production
and distribution and consumption of goods and services and their management. He gained
a first class Honours degree in economics. economy. e . c . o . n . o . m . y . economy.
economy means the system of production and distribution and consumption. A capitalist
economy. edge. e . d . g . e . edge. edge means a sharp
side formed by the intersection of two surfaces of an object. He rounded the edges of the
box. edition. e . d . i . t . i . o . n . edition.
edition means all of the identical copies of something offered to the public at the
same time. It was too late for the morning edition.
editor. e . d . i . t . o . r . editor. editor means a person responsible for the editorial
aspects of publication; the person who determines the final content of a text. The editor of
the Daily Telegraph. educate. e . d . u . c . a . t . e . educate.
educate means give an education to. We must educate our youngsters better.
educated. e . d . u . c . a . t . e . d . educated. educated means having or based on relevant
experience. An educated guess. education. e . d . u . c . a . t . i . o . n
. education. education means the activities of educating or instructing; activities that
impart knowledge or skill. He received no formal education.
educational. e . d . u . c . a . t . i . o . n . a . l . educational. educational means
relating to the process of education. Pupils with special educational needs.
effect. e . f . f . e . c . t . effect. effect means a phenomenon that follows and is caused
by some previous phenomenon. The magnetic effect was greater when the rod was lengthwise.
effective. e . f . f . e . c . t . i . v . e . effective. effective means producing or
capable of producing an intended result or having a striking effect. Effective steps
toward peace. effectively. e . f . f . e . c . t . i . v
. e . l . y . effectively. effectively means in an effective manner. These are real problems
that can be dealt with most effectively by rational discussion.
efficient. e . f . f . i . c . i . e . n . t . efficient. efficient means being effective
without wasting time or effort or expense. An efficient production manager.
efficiently. e . f . f . i . c . i . e . n . t . l . y . efficiently. efficiently means
in an efficient manner. He functions efficiently. effort. e . f . f . o . r . t . effort. effort
means earnest and conscientious activity intended to do or accomplish something. Made an effort
to cover all the reading material. e.g. e . g . e.g. e.g. is an abbreviation
for as an example. Take ribbon snakes, for example.
egg. e . g . g . egg. egg means animal reproductive body consisting of an ovum or embryo together
with nutritive and protective envelopes. A baby bird hatching from its egg.
either. e . i . t . h . e . r . either. either means after a negative statement used as an
intensive meaning something like or also. He isn't stupid, but he isn't exactly a genius
either. elbow. e . l . b . o . w . elbow. elbow means
hinge joint between the forearm and upper arm and the corresponding joint in the forelimb
of a quadruped. He slipped and fell, badly bruising an elbow.
elderly. e . l . d . e . r . l . y . elderly. elderly means advanced in years; aged is pronounced
as two syllables. Elderly members of the society. elect. e . l . e . c . t . elect. elect means
select by a vote for an office or membership. We elected him chairman of the board.
election. e . l . e . c . t . i . o . n . election. election means a vote to select the winner
of a position or political office. The results of the election will be announced tonight.
electric. e . l . e . c . t . r . i . c . electric. electric means using or providing or producing
or transmitting or operated by electricity. Her electric guitar.
electrical. e . l . e . c . t . r . i . c . a . l . electrical. electrical means relating
to or concerned with electricity. Electrical and mechanical engineering industries.
electricity. e . l . e . c . t . r . i . c . i . t . y . electricity. electricity means
energy made available by the flow of electric charge through a conductor. They built a car
that runs on electricity. electronic. e . l . e . c . t . r . o . n
. i . c . electronic. electronic means of or relating to electronics; concerned with
or using devices that operate on principles governing the behavior of electrons. Electronic
devices. elegant. e . l . e . g . a . n . t . elegant.
elegant means refined and tasteful in appearance or behavior or style. She was elegant to her
fingertips. element. e . l . e . m . e . n . t . element.
element means an abstract part of something. The grammatical elements of a sentence.
elevator. e . l . e . v . a . t . o . r . elevator. elevator means lifting device consisting of
a platform or cage that is raised and lowered mechanically in a vertical shaft in order
to move people from one floor to another in a building. We'll have to take the elevator.
eliminate. e . l . i . m . i . n . a . t . e . eliminate. eliminate means terminate or
take out. Let's eliminate the course on Akkadian hieroglyphics.
else. e . l . s . e . else. else means additional to or different from this one or place or
time or manner. She ignored everything else. elsewhere. e . l . s . e . w . h . e . r . e
. elsewhere. elsewhere means in or to another place. Look elsewhere for the answer.
e mail. e mail. e mail means a system of world-wide electronic communication in which a computer
user can compose a message at one terminal that is generated at the recipient's terminal
when he logs in. You can contact us by e-mail. embarrass. e . m . b . a . r . r . a . s . s
. embarrass. embarrass means cause to be embarrassed; cause to feel self-conscious. His clumsiness
embarrassed him. embarrassing. e . m . b . a . r . r . a . s
. s . i . n . g . embarrassing. embarrassing means hard to deal with; especially causing
pain or embarrassment. An embarrassing pause followed his remark.
embarrassed. e . m . b . a . r . r . a . s . s . e . d . embarrassed. embarrassed means
feeling or caused to feel uneasy and self-conscious. Felt embarrassed at the extravagant praise.
embarrassment. e . m . b . a . r . r . a . s . s . m . e . n . t . embarrassment. embarrassment
means the state of being embarrassed. He is currently suffering financial embarrassments
emerge. e . m . e . r . g . e . emerge. emerge means come out into view, as from concealment.
Suddenly, the proprietor emerged from his office
emergency. e . m . e . r . g . e . n . c . y . emergency. emergency means a sudden unforeseen
crisis that requires immediate action. He never knew what to do in an emergency.
emotion. e . m . o . t . i . o . n . emotion. emotion means any strong feeling. He lost
control of his emotions. emotional. e . m . o . t . i . o . n . a . l
. emotional. emotional means determined or actuated by emotion rather than reason. It
was an emotional judgment emotionally. e . m . o . t . i . o . n . a
. l . l . y . emotionally. emotionally means in an emotional manner. At the funeral he
spoke emotionally emphasis. e . m . p . h . a . s . i . s . emphasis.
emphasis means special importance or significance. The red light gave the central figure increased
emphasis emphasize. e . m . p . h . a . s . i . z . e
. emphasize. emphasize means to stress, single out as important. Dr. Jones emphasizes exercise
in addition to a change in diet empire. e . m . p . i . r . e . empire. empire
means the domain ruled by an emperor or empress; the region over which imperial dominion is
exercised. The British empire. employ. e . m . p . l . o . y . employ. employ
means the state of being employed or having a job. He was in the employ of the city.
unemployed. u . n . e . m . p . l . o . y . e . d . unemployed. unemployed means not
engaged in a gainful occupation. Unemployed workers marched on the capital.
employee. e . m . p . l . o . y . e . e . employee. employee means a worker who is hired to perform
a job. The company has over 500 employees. employer. e . m . p . l . o . y . e . r . employer.
employer means a person or firm that employs workers. Very good employers.
employment. e . m . p . l . o . y . m . e . n . t . employment. employment means the
state of being employed or having a job. They are looking for employment.
unemployment. u . n . e . m . p . l . o . y . m . e . n . t . unemployment. unemployment
means the state of being unemployed or not having a job. Unemployment is a serious social
evil. empty. e . m . p . t . y . empty. empty means
holding or containing nothing. An empty glass. enable. e . n . a . b . l . e . enable. enable
means render capable or able for some task. This skill will enable you to find a job on
Wall Street. encounter. e . n . c . o . u . n . t . e . r
. encounter. encounter means a casual or unexpected convergence. Come together. He still remembers
their meeting in Paris. I'll probably encounter you at the meeting.
encourage. e . n . c . o . u . r . a . g . e . encourage. encourage means contribute to
the progress or growth of. I am encouraging the use of computers in the classroom.
encouragement. e . n . c . o . u . r . a . g . e . m . e . n . t . encouragement. encouragement
means the expression of approval and support. A few words of encouragement.
end. e . n . d . end. end means either extremity of something that has length. She knotted
the end of the thread. in the end. in the end. in the end means after
a very lengthy period of time. She will succeed in the end.
ending. e . n . d . i . n . g . ending. ending means the end of a word. His stories usually
have a happy ending. enemy. e . n . e . m . y . enemy. enemy means
an opposing military force. The enemy attacked at dawn.
energy. e . n . e . r . g . y . energy. energy means the capacity of a physical system to
do work; the units of energy are joules or ergs. Energy can take a wide variety of forms.
engage. e . n . g . a . g . e . engage. engage means carry out or participate in an activity.
She engaged many activities. engaged. e . n . g . a . g . e . d . engaged.
engaged means having ones attention or mind or energy engaged. She keeps herself fully
engaged with volunteer activities. engine. e . n . g . i . n . e . engine. engine
means motor that converts thermal energy to mechanical work. My car had to have a new
engine. engineer. e . n . g . i . n . e . e . r . engineer.
engineer means a person who uses scientific knowledge to solve practical problems. A mechanical
engineer. engineering. e . n . g . i . n . e . e . r
. i . n . g . engineering. engineering means the practical application of science to commerce
or industry. The bridge is a triumph of modern engineering.
enjoy. e . n . j . o . y . enjoy. enjoy means derive or receive pleasure from; get enjoyment
from; take pleasure in. We thoroughly enjoyed our time in Japan.
enjoyable. e . n . j . o . y . a . b . l . e . enjoyable. enjoyable means affording satisfaction
or pleasure. The company was enjoyable. enjoyment. e . n . j . o . y . m . e . n . t
. enjoyment. enjoyment means the pleasure felt when having a good time. He spoiled my
enjoyment of the game. enormous. e . n . o . r . m . o . u . s . enormous.
enormous means extraordinarily large in size or extent or amount or power or degree. An
enormous boulder. enough. e . n . o . u . g . h . enough. enough
means as much as necessary. I hadn't trained enough for the game.
ensure. e . n . s . u . r . e . ensure. ensure means make certain of. This nest egg will
ensure a nice retirement for us. enter. e . n . t . e . r . enter. enter means
to come or go into. The boat entered an area of shallow marshes.
entertain. e . n . t . e . r . t . a . i . n . entertain. entertain means provide entertainment
for. He entertained the notion of moving to South America.
entertaining. e . n . t . e . r . t . a . i . n . i . n . g . entertaining. entertaining
means agreeably diverting or amusing. an entertaining puppet show.
entertainer. e . n . t . e . r . t . a . i . n . e . r . entertainer. entertainer means
a person who tries to please or amuse. She remains one of the top entertainers of all
time. entertainment. e . n . t . e . r . t . a . i
. n . m . e . n . t . entertainment. entertainment means an activity that is diverting and that
holds the attention. The entertainment was provided by a folk band.
enthusiasm. e . n . t . h . u . s . i . a . s . m . enthusiasm. enthusiasm means a feeling
of excitement. Enthusiasm for his program is growing.
enthusiastic. e . n . t . h . u . s . i . a . s . t . i . c . enthusiastic. enthusiastic
means having or showing great excitement and interest. Enthusiastic crowds filled the streets.
entire. e . n . t . i . r . e . entire. entire means constituting the full quantity or extent;
complete. An entire town devastated by an earthquake.
entirely. e . n . t . i . r . e . l . y . entirely. entirely means to a complete degree or to
the full or entire extent. It was entirely different from what we expected.
entitle. e . n . t . i . t . l . e . entitle. entitle means give the right to. The Freedom
of Information Act entitles you to request your FBI file.
entrance. e . n . t . r . a . n . c . e . entrance. entrance means something that provides access.
They waited at the entrance to the garden. entry. e . n . t . r . y . entry. entry means
an item inserted in a written record. More keyboarding staff are required for data entry.
envelope. e . n . v . e . l . o . p . e . envelope. envelope means a flat rectangular paper container
for papers. She tore open the envelope and frantically read the letter.
environment. e . n . v . i . r . o . n . m . e . n . t . environment. environment means
the totality of surrounding condition. She longed for the comfortable environment of
his living room. environmental. e . n . v . i . r . o . n . m
. e . n . t . a . l . environmental. environmental means concerned with the ecological effects
of altering the environment. Environmental pollution.
equal. e . q . u . a . l . equal. equal means well matched; having the same quantity, value,
or measure as another. All men are equal before the law.
equally. e . q . u . a . l . l . y . equally. equally means to the same degree. They were
equally beautiful. equipment. e . q . u . i . p . m . e . n . t
. equipment. equipment means an instrumentality needed for an undertaking or to perform a
service. A useful piece of equipment for the kitchen.
equivalent. e . q . u . i . v . a . l . e . n . t . equivalent. equivalent means equal
in amount or value. Gave one six blows and the other a equivalent number.
era. e . r . a . era. era means a period marked by distinctive character or reckoned from
a fixed point or event. When she left the firm, it was the end of an era .
error. e . r . r . o . r . error. error means a wrong action attributable to bad judgment
or ignorance or inattention. I could understand his English in spite of his grammatical error.
escape. e . s . c . a . p . e . escape. escape means run away from confinement. The convicted
murderer escaped from a high security prison. especially. e . s . p . e . c . i . a . l
. l . y . especially. especially means to a distinctly greater extent or degree than
is common. He was especially fussy about spelling. essay. e . s . s . a . y . essay. essay means
an analytic or interpretive literary composition. An essay on the causes of the First World
War. essential. e . s . s . e . n . t . i . a . l
. essential. essential means absolutely necessary; vitally necessary. Funds essential to the
completion of the project. essentially. e . s . s . e . n . t . i . a
. l . l . y . essentially. essentially means at bottom or by one's (or its) very nature.
The argument was essentially a technical one. establish. e . s . t . a . b . l . i . s . h
. establish. establish means set up or found. She establishes a literacy program.
estate. e . s . t . a . t . e . estate. estate means everything you own; all of your assets
(whether real property or personal property) and liabilities. The family owned a large
estate on Long Island. estimate. e . s . t . i . m . a . t . e . estimate.
estimate means an approximate calculation of quantity or degree or worth. An estimate
of what it would cost. etc. e . t . c . etc. etc means continuing
in the same way. A shop which sells cards, calendars, wrapping paper etc.
ethnic. e . t . h . n . i . c . ethnic. ethnic means denoting or deriving from or distinctive
of the ways of living built up by a group of people. The country is divided along ethnic
lines. even. e . v . e . n . even. even means used
as an intensive especially to indicate something unexpected. I don't have even a dollar!
evening. e . v . e . n . i . n . g . evening. evening means the latter part of the day (the
period of decreasing daylight from late afternoon until nightfall). He enjoyed the evening light
across the lake. event. e . v . e . n . t . event. event means
something that happens at a given place and time. In that event, the first possibility
is excluded. eventually. e . v . e . n . t . u . a . l
. l . y . eventually. eventually means within an indefinite time or at an unspecified future
time. He will understand eventually. ever. e . v . e . r . ever. ever means at
any time. Did you ever smoke? every. e . v . e . r . y . every. every means
each and all of a series of entities or intervals as specified. Every third seat.
everyone. e . v . e . r . y . o . n . e . everyone. everyone means every person; all people. Everyone
cheered and clapped. everything. e . v . e . r . y . t . h . i
. n . g . everything. everything means all things. Everything had gone.
everywhere. e . v . e . r . y . w . h . e . r . e . everywhere. everywhere means to
or in any or all places. You find fast food stores everywhere.
evidence. e . v . i . d . e . n . c . e . evidence. evidence means your basis for belief or disbelief;
knowledge on which to base belief. The evidence that smoking causes lung cancer is very compelling.
evil. e . v . i . l . evil. evil means morally bad or wrong. An evil influence.
ex. e . x . ex. ex means former and still living. His ex-wife.
exact. e . x . a . c . t . exact. exact means marked by strict and particular and complete
accordance with fact. Hit the exact center of the target.
exactly. e . x . a . c . t . l . y . exactly. exactly means indicating exactness or preciseness.
He was doing exactly what she had told him to do.
exaggerate. e . x . a . g . g . e . r . a . t . e . exaggerate. exaggerate means to
enlarge beyond bounds or the truth. Tended to romanticize and exaggerate this 'gracious
Old South' imagery. exaggerated. e . x . a . g . g . e . r . a
. t . e . d . exaggerated. exaggerated means represented as greater than is true or reasonable.
An exaggerated opinion of oneself. exam. e . x . a . m . exam. exam means a set
of questions or exercises evaluating skill or knowledge. When the exam was stolen the
professor had to make a new set of questions. examination. e . x . a . m . i . n . a . t
. i . o . n . examination. examination means the act of examining something closely (as
for mistakes). Sit an examination in mathematics. examine. e . x . a . m . i . n . e . examine.
examine means consider in detail and subject to an analysis in order to discover essential
features or meaning. Examine the evidence in a criminal trial.
example. e . x . a . m . p . l . e . example. example means an item of information that
is representative of a type. This patient provides a typical example of the syndrome.
excellent. e . x . c . e . l . l . e . n . t . excellent. excellent means of the highest
quality. The school has excellent teachers. except. e . x . c . e . p . t . except. except
means prevent from being included or considered or accepted. The bad results were excepted
from the report. exception. e . x . c . e . p . t . i . o . n
. exception. exception means a deliberate act of omission. With the exception of the
children, everyone was told the news. exchange. e . x . c . h . a . n . g . e . exchange.
exchange means the act of changing one thing for another thing. Adam was promised immortality
in exchange for his disobedience. in exchange. in exchange. in exchange means
an act of giving something to someone and receiving something in return. Would you like
my old TV in exchange for this camera? excite. e . x . c . i . t . e . excite. excite
means arouse or elicit a feeling. The prospect of a year in India greatly excited her.
exciting. e . x . c . i . t . i . n . g . exciting. exciting means creating or arousing excitement.
An exciting account of her trip. excited. e . x . c . i . t . e . d . excited.
excited means excessively affected by emotion. He would become excited over nothing at all.
excitement. e . x . c . i . t . e . m . e . n . t . excitement. excitement means the
feeling of lively and cheerful joy. He could hardly conceal his excitement when she agreed.
exclude. e . x . c . l . u . d . e . exclude. exclude means prevent from being included
or considered or accepted. The bad results were excluded from the report.
excluding. e . x . c . l . u . d . i . n . g . excluding. excluding means not including.
Excluding water, half of the body's weight is protein.
excuse. e . x . c . u . s . e . excuse. excuse means a defense of some offensive behavior
or some failure to keep a promise. Every day he had a new excuse for not getting a job.
executive. e . x . e . c . u . t . i . v . e . executive. executive means having the function
of carrying out plans or orders. The executive branch.
exercise. e . x . e . r . c . i . s . e . exercise. exercise means the activity of exerting your
muscles in various ways to keep fit. The doctor recommended regular exercise.
exhibit. e . x . h . i . b . i . t . exhibit. exhibit means show an attribute, property,
knowledge, or skill. He exhibits a great talent. exhibition. e . x . h . i . b . i . t . i
. o . n . exhibition. exhibition means the act of exhibiting. A remarkable exhibition
of musicianship. exist. e . x . i . s . t . exist. exist means
have an existence, be extant. He could barely exist on such a low wage.
existence. e . x . i . s . t . e . n . c . e . existence. existence means the state or
fact of existing. Laws in existence for centuries. exit. e . x . i . t . exit. exit means an
opening that permits escape or release. The canyon had only one exit.
expand. e . x . p . a . n . d . expand. expand means extend in one or more directions. The
dough expands. expect. e . x . p . e . c . t . expect. expect
means regard something as probable or likely. The meteorologists are expecting rain for
tomorrow. expected. e . x . p . e . c . t . e . d . expected.
expected means considered likely or probable to happen or arrive. Prepared for the expected
attack. unexpected. u . n . e . x . p . e . c . t
. e . d . unexpected. unexpected means not expected or anticipated. Unexpected guests.
unexpectedly. u . n . e . x . p . e . c . t . e . d . l . y . unexpectedly. unexpectedly
means in a way that was not expected. Her brother showed up at the wedding unexpectedly.
expectation. e . x . p . e . c . t . a . t . i . o . n . expectation. expectation means
belief about (or mental picture of) the future. We are confident in our expectation of a full
recovery. expense. e . x . p . e . n . s . e . expense.
expense means amounts paid for goods and services that may be currently tax deductible. He kept
a careful record of his expenses at the meeting. expensive. e . x . p . e . n . s . i . v . e
. expensive. expensive means high in price or charging high prices. Expensive clothes.
experience. e . x . p . e . r . i . e . n . c . e . experience. experience means the
accumulation of knowledge or skill that results from direct participation in events or activities.
Experience is the best teacher. experienced. e . x . p . e . r . i . e . n
. c . e . d . experienced. experienced means having experience; having knowledge or skill
from observation or participation.an experienced teacher.
experiment. e . x . p . e . r . i . m . e . n . t . experiment. experiment means the
act of conducting a controlled test or investigation. It was an experiment in living
expert. e . x . p . e . r . t . expert. expert means a person with special knowledge or ability
who performs skillfully. An expert on modern literature .
explain. e . x . p . l . a . i . n . explain. explain means make plain and comprehensible.
He explained the laws of physics to his students. explanation. e . x . p . l . a . n . a . t
. i . o . n . explanation. explanation means a statement that makes something comprehensible
by describing the relevant structure or operation or circumstances. The explanation was very
simple. explode. e . x . p . l . o . d . e . explode.
explode means cause to burst with a violent release of energy. We exploded the nuclear
bomb. explore. e . x . p . l . o . r . e . explore.
explore means inquire into. The students had to explore the history of the Second World
War for their history project. explosion. e . x . p . l . o . s . i . o . n
. explosion. explosion means the act of exploding or bursting something. The explosion of the
firecrackers awoke the children. export. e . x . p . o . r . t . export. export
means sell or transfer abroad. We export less than we import and have a negative trade balance.
expose. e . x . p . o . s . e . expose. expose means expose or make accessible to some action
or influence. Expose the blanket to sunshine. express. e . x . p . r . e . s . s . express.
express means give expression to. She expressed her disappointment
expression. e . x . p . r . e . s . s . i . o . n . expression. expression means the
feelings expressed on a person's face. A sad expression.
extend. e . x . t . e . n . d . extend. extend means extend in scope or range or area. Extend
the range of applications. extension. e . x . t . e . n . s . i . o . n
. extension. extension means a mutually agreed delay in the date set for the completion of
a job or payment of a debt. They applied for an extension of the loan.
extensive. e . x . t . e . n . s . i . v . e . extensive. extensive means large in spatial
extent or range or scope or quantity. An extensive Roman settlement in northwest England.
extent. e . x . t . e . n . t . extent. extent means the point or degree to which something
extends. The extent of the damage. extra. e . x . t . r . a . extra. extra means
more than is needed, desired, or required. Found some extra change lying on the dresser.
extraordinary. e . x . t . r . a . o . r . d . i . n . a . r . y . extraordinary. extraordinary
means beyond what is ordinary or usual; highly unusual or exceptional or remarkable. An extraordinary
achievement. extreme. e . x . t . r . e . m . e . extreme.
extreme means of the greatest possible degree or extent or intensity. Extreme caution.
